{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489128"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:05:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:05:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"597"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/597"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.02,0.08,0.73,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"597"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58854"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/597"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"597"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44262"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"471"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"878"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7275"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8002"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18393"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42106"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58854"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a one day history of nausea and vomiting. This is accompanied with severe abdominal pain, lethargy, and confusion. His partner is concerned he has overdosed on one of his regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis medical history includes major depressive disorder (with two previous suicide attempts), hypertension, hyperlipidaemia, congestive heart failure and atrial fibrillation. His regular medications are perindopril, atorvastatin, bisoprolol, furosemide, dapagliflozin, apixaban, and digoxin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his heart rate is 55/min, blood pressure 90/80mmHg and temperature 37.2\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInitial investigations reveal serum digoxin level of 2.5 \u00b5g/L (therapeutic range 0.5-2.0)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following markers is the most important to check next?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anion gap","CRP + ESR levels","Troponin level","Serum potassium level","Creatinine Kinase level"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a case of digoxin toxicity. His digoxin level is high and is consistent with his clinical symptoms of nausea, vomiting, lethargy and confusion. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum potassium\u003C/strong\u003E is the most important marker in cases of digoxin toxicity as the presence of hyperkalaemia is a predictor of mortality. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn a study of 91 patients with acute digoxin poisoning, if the initial serum potassium level was \u0026gt;5.5mmol/L, none of the patients survived. Moreover, a combination of bradycardia and hyperkalaemia strongly predicted fatality, even in cases of appropriate antidote (Digibind) administration. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt the same time, with \u003Cem\u003Ehypokalaemia\u003C/em\u003E digoxin toxicity is also worsened. This is because digoxin normally binds to the ATPase pump on the same site as potassium. When potassium levels are low, digoxin can more easily bind to the ATPase pump, exerting the inhibitory effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECreatinine kinase \u003C/strong\u003Eis unrelated to digoxin toxicity. \u003Cstrong\u003ETroponin \u003C/strong\u003Eis unrelated to digoxin toxicity but is relevant in diagnosing myocardial infarction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECRP + ESR levels \u003C/strong\u003Eare unrelated to digoxin toxicity - they are useful in monitoring patients with inflammatory conditions. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnion gap\u003C/strong\u003E can be used to assess metabolic disturbances, but is not a prognostic marker in digoxin toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["It is important to check the serum potassium level in patients with suspected digoxin poisoning"],"references":["Manini AF, Nelson LS \u0026 Hoffman RS 2011, Prognostic utility of serum potassium in chronic digoxin toxicity: a case-control study, American Journal of Cardiovascular Drugs, Vol. 11, Issue 3, pp. 173-178.","Pincus M 2016, Management of digoxin toxicity, Australian Prescriber, Vol. 39, pp. 18-20, \u003C https://www.nps.org.au/australian-prescriber/articles/management-of-digoxin-toxicity\u003E.","Levine M \u0026 O\u0027Connor A.\u0027Digitalis (cardiac glycoside) poisoning\u0027. UptoDate website. 2022.  Viewed on January 2023. Available via: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/digitalis-cardiac-glycoside-poisoning?search=digoxin%20toxicity\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1~89\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1#H16"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44262"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"597"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}